Neuroimmunomodulation
DOI: 10.1159/000489635
vided unclear results. However, increased inflammation 
during the early development appears to be related to an 
ADHD phenotype. ADHD is a highly hereditary disorder; 
therefore, it might be expected that polymorphisms in in­
flammatory-related genes are present in patients. Al­
though some studies have found this association, there is 
no consensus about which genes are affected. To sum up, 
there have been indications for a role of the immune sys­
tem in the pathophysiology of ADHD. However, well-de­
signed studies are still needed to confirm this hypothesis.
